<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / The Week Ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Results Due
THREE of the biggest UK insurance companies will still be in the red when
they report pre-tax losses for the first half of 1992 this week. But with
rate increases in the home, motor and commercial insurance markets taking
hold and companies avoiding the weather losses of recent years, there are
some glints of light on the horizon.
General Accident, which reports tomorrow, is widely expected to do best with
pre-tax losses cut to between Pounds 20m and Pounds 30m compared to a
deficit of Pounds 105.2m at the same stage in 1991. GA may even have made a
small profit in the second quarter, according to some analysts.
Commercial Union, the most successful and aggressive UK insurer, is on
Wednesday expected to report losses of around Pounds 30m, a deterioration on
last year's Pounds 26.3m.
Royal Insurance, whose balance sheet is weakest, is on Thursday expected to
register losses of between Pounds 70m and Pounds 100m, compared to a deficit
of Pounds 97m last year.
Hanson, the Anglo-American conglomerate, is expected to report a significant
fall in pre-tax profits for the nine months to June when it announces its
results on Thursday. Pre-tax profits are likely to have fallen from Pounds
967m to around Pounds 760m. However, last year's results were boosted by
acquisition benefits. Net debt, which is US dollar denominated, is expected
to have fallen to Pounds 1.1bn because of the weakness of the dollar.
British Airways' first quarter figures tomorrow should reveal pre-tax
profits of around Pounds 90m compared Pounds 9m a year earlier. The market
will also be looking for news of progress on cost cutting, the recent deal
to take a Dollars 750m stake in USAir and clues over the impact of price
wars in the airline industry.
