FT  10 AUG 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
We are promised the sight of dog eating dog in the last of the present
series of Antenna (8.00 BBC2). Magazine editor Richard Smith has a go at
other journalists for the way in which they present stories about science.
He argues that we are becoming increasingly distrustful of science because
we are misled by newspapers which make claims such as 'British breakthrough
likely to end asthma suffering'.
It doesn't help the cause of science too much, of course, when scientists go
around claiming to have achieved cold fusion at room temperature, but it is
always easier to kick the messenger in the teeth.
Smith is editor of the doctors' magazine, the British Medical Journal.
Doctors emerge rather badly by all accounts from the C4 programme Secret
History (9.00) which describes an experiment in which 400 men died. They
thought they were being treated for syphilis but actually the doctors were
merely observing the development of the disease.
ITV screens the first of three documentaries, China Rising (10.40), about
the development of Chinese cities, beginning with Shanghai, once a
cosmopolitan highspot.
</TEXT>
