<TEXT>
Mr Francisco Fernandez Ordonez, the former foreign minister who helped guide
Spain's integration into the European Community, died yesterday after a long
illness, AP reports from Madrid. He was 62.
Mr Fernandez Ordonez had asked to be relieved from his post as foreign
minister in June. He had suffered from cancer of the liver and gall bladder
problems and was also operated on for an intestinal ailment in 1989.
Formerly known as the untiring workhorse of the Socialist government of Mr
Felipe Gonzalez, the prime minister, Mr Fernandez Ordonez took over at the
Foreign Ministry in 1985, three years after the Socialists took office. One
of the most popular and respected figures in the Gonzalez government, he was
replaced on June 26 by Mr Javier Solana.
News reports said Mr Gonzalez interrupted his summer holidays on Thursday to
visit Mr Fernandez Ordonez early yesterday.
A tax lawyer by training, Mr Fernandez Ordonez was outspoken in his advocacy
of EC unity - and Spain's controversial efforts to rise to the challenge.
