<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 92 / UN wants observers in S Africa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, AGENCIES and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, CAPE TOWN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations proposes to station 30 observers in South Africa to help
bring about a peaceful transition to a multi-racial democracy, write Michael
Littlejohns and Agencies in New York.
The observer force was recommended by UN secretary general Mr Boutros
Boutros Ghali yesterday in a report to the UN Security Council after the
recent visit to South Africa by his envoy, Mr Cyrus Vance.
Mr Boutros Ghali said the observers would draw on the experience of 10
temporary UN observers sent to monitor the two-day strike and protest
rallies in South Africa this week.
'The observers would be stationed in agreed upon locations, in various parts
of South Africa,' he said. They could, if necessary, be joined by personnel
from the Commonwealth, the European Community and the Organisation of
African States.
Mr Boutros Ghali also recommended that 'an eminent and impartial person' -
not necessarily a foreigner - be appointed to give impetus to new talks on
constitutional arrangements in South Africa.
The African National Congress has vowed not to resume constitutional talks
until the government meets a number of demands, including measures to end
violence, which has taken thousands of lives, especially in black townships.
A South African prosecutor said yesterday he was examining new evidence of a
state role in the 1985 killing of prominent black activist Matthew Goniwe,
Reuter reports from Cape Town.
Mr Michael Hodgen said a police team interviewed unidentified witnesses
provided by newspapers including Johannesburg's Weekly Mail.
The Weekly Mail said it had submitted evidence including the names of state
hit-squad members responsible for the murder of Goniwe and colleagues on a
remote highway.
</TEXT>
