<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 92 / Italy boardroom reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S new government yesterday sent the strongest signal to date of its
determination to shake up and privatise the country's public sector by
pushing through a revolutionary slimming-down of the boards of the country's
four biggest state-owned companies.
IRI, the biggest state holding company, ENI, the energy and chemicals
concern, ENEL, the state electricity authority, and INA, the state insurance
agency, will see their boards shrink to just three members.
Only one member, the chairman, will remain a political appointment. A new
position of chief executive will be created, to be occupied by the
companies' current director-general, a non-political post. The third board
member will be a senior civil servant from one of the key ministries
involved in the privatisation process.
The present chairmen, Mr Franco Nobili at IRI, Mr Gabriele Cagliari at ENI,
Mr Franco Viezzoli at ENEL and Mr Lorenzo Pallesi at INA, will all retain
their jobs, at least until the next shareholders' meetings in April.
However, at a press conference last night, Mr Giuliano Amato, the prime
minister, indicated the longer-term outlook for IRI and ENI in particular
involved big changes, expecially disposals.
Mr Amato, flanked by Mr Piero Barucci, treasury minister, Mr Franco
Reviglio, budget minister, and Mr Giuseppe Guarino, industry minister, the
chief architects of the privatisation drive, stressed that all four groups
would eventually be sold to the public.
In the case of IRI and ENI, Italy's two biggest public-sector industrial
concerns, reducing losses in some subsidiaries would be a first step. Once
quoted, the companies would be open to foreign alliances to improve their
international coverage and would represent a 'new Italian national
industry', he said.
The new boards will replace the dozens of committees and executive groups,
largely comprising political appointees, which have dominated the four
companies in the past. ENI's main board has 15 members, mainly put forward
by the governing parties; IRI has 14.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
