FT  08 AUG 92 / Bush says Iraq will be forced to comply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush insisted yesterday that Iraq would be forced to comply
with United Nations resolutions despite Baghdad's threat to deny weapons'
inspectors access to government ministries.
At the same time a newly arrived UN weapons inspection team, due to begin
work in Baghdad today, agreed to a one-day postponement because today is a
holiday in Iraq.
Referring to Iraq's recent resistance to weapons inspections, Mr Bush said:
'I can't tell how much of this is bluster. But they are going to comply with
UN resolutions. I am absolutely certain of that.'
The latest team of 22 UN inspectors is headed by a Russian, Mr Nikita
Smidovich. Their visit is the latest attempt to discover remaining Iraqi
stocks of nuclear, chemical and other weapons of mass destruction.
Previous UN inspectors were barred for 18 days from a ministry of
agriculture building in Baghdad, before Iraq bowed to growing threats of
renewed military intervention.
On Thursday, the Iraqis threw down a further challenge, warning that no more
visits to ministries would be permitted, a condition which a Pentagon
spokesman in Washington described as 'preposterous'.
Mr Smidovich has given no indication whether ministries are on the list of
sites inspectors want to visit on this trip.
But he said before leaving Bahrain: 'We have our orders and our rights are
clear. We can visit any place in Iraq.'
Mr Bush has refused to rule out the use of force if Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein again defies the UN.
</TEXT>
