<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 92 / Egypt moves on customs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Egypt took a further step towards a market economy yesterday, abolishing
customs concessions for state-owned companies and ending a ban on some
imports, Reuter reports from Cairo. A presidential decree setting new
customs rates went into effect at midnight at ports of entry, allowing
imports of 30 previously banned categories and cutting an import blacklist
to 75 items. Freeing trade and ending prerogatives enjoyed by the subsidised
public sector have been high on a reform agenda agreed with the IMF.
</TEXT>
