FT  07 AUG 92 / BNL probe to subpoena CIA Iraq documents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE HOUSE banking committee yesterday voted to subpoena secret Iraqi-related
documents from the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and other agencies of
the US government, in a move that could considerably broaden the
investigation of more than Dollars 5bn of unauthorised Iraqi loans made in
the 1980s by the Atlanta branch of Italy's Banca Nazionale del Lavoro (BNL).
Subpoena power was awarded against all of the US branches of BNL. The
committee said subpoena authority was also granted against Mr Christopher
Drogoul, former BNL Atlanta branch manager.
Mr Drogoul claimed last April that the US and Italian governments knew of
the BNL loans, which helped to finance the nuclear and chemical weapons
projects of Mr Saddam Hussein.
The Bush administration has denied any knowledge of the illicit BNL loans.
Mr Drogoul, who in June struck a surprise deal with the Department of
Justice under which many fraud charges were dropped in return for his
co-operating with prosecutors, will be called to testify by the committee in
mid-September. His appearance in Congress will come just after he is
sentenced by an Atlanta judge.
The committee will also subpoena documents about BNL from the National
Security Agency (NSA), the secretive electronic surveillance agency that is
believed by congressional investigators to have intercepted many of the
thousands of telexes between Baghdad and BNL Atlanta over a five-year
period.
'This moves our BNL investigation on to a new plane,' said a spokesman for
the committee which may also subpoena bank regulators in New York and Texas
and at the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation and the Office of the
Comptroller of the Currency.
