<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 92 / Iraq bars inspection teams from ministries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS, Middle East Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IRAQ yesterday stepped up its political challenge to the United Nations in
general and US President George Bush in particular by warning that it would
not tolerate further inspections of Baghdad ministries by teams of UN
inspectors.
The US immediately denounced the statement. Mr Bush pledged that Washington
would guarantee UN inspectors access to suspected Iraqi weapons sites,
saying: 'United Nations resolutions will be honoured in full.'
Mr Marlin Fitzwater, White House spokesman, added that military planning had
already been undertaken to ensure the enforcement of such resolutions.
Oil prices rose on fears that the US might eventually use force against
Iraq.
Mr Hamed Youssef Hammadi, Iraq's information minister, said his government
rejected any new attempt to enter ministries because the aim was to 'hurt
Iraq's sovereignty and independence'.
A UN inspection team seeking evidence of Iraq's nuclear and chemical weapons
programme was denied entry to the agriculture ministry for 18 days last
month in defiance of Security Council resolutions.
On gaining access to the building, inspectors found nothing relating to
Iraq's weapons programme and President Saddam Hussein claimed Mr Bush had
been politically humiliated.
Iraqi officials were jubilant that the UN team had been delayed for so long
and that Americans in the team did not search the building.
Mr Hammadi said yesterday: 'The entering of ministries or the headquarters
of ministries will not be agreed to. This is one thing. As far as other
places are concerned the inspection teams can visit any place in the
country. We want to end this silly chapter as soon as possible.'
A new 22-strong UN team is preparing to leave Bahrain for Baghdad. Mr Rolf
Ekeus, who heads the UN effort to destroy all Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, last week told Mr Tariq Aziz, Iraq's deputy prime minister,
that there would be a swift reaction if Baghdad again tried to block
inspection.
In New York, Mr Michael Newlin, deputy head of the UN inspection commission,
said the new probe of Iraq's major weapons capability would start on
schedule tomorrow. A senior UN official said inspectors would not hesitate
to enter a ministerial building if they suspected it contained relevant
material.
The statement by Mr Hammadi keeps the issue high on the US political agenda
as Mr Bush prepares for the Republican convention on August 17.
The Iraqi leader boasted of his part in the political downfall of Mrs
Margaret Thatcher. Baghdad radio has been promising similar treatment for Mr
Bush.
</TEXT>
