<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 92 / M-way service sites to increase as controls are eased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY MORE motorway service areas will be built under new arrangements
announced by the government yesterday.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said the private sector, instead of
the government, would now decide where to build the service areas. The
minimum distance between them would be cut from 30 miles to 15 miles.
Strict rules will prevent service areas expanding into other activities such
as shopping and entertainment, however, because the department does not wish
them to become destinations in their own right.
There were fears such a development would generate extra traffic and that
existing facilities in nearby communities might be jeopardised.
At present, sites for motorway service areas are identified by the transport
department. It seeks planning permission for the areas and acquires the
necessary land.
The department lets the sites to private companies which build and operate
the service areas under long leases in return for premium payments and
peppercorn rents.
The new system will leave it to the private sector to decide where to build
service areas. Companies will seek planning permission from local
authorities and acquire the land.
Some curbs will still apply. Free parking, toilets and picnic areas will
have to be provided, all facilities will have to be be available to the
disabled, fuel will have to be on sale 24 hours a day and alcohol sales will
be banned.
Mr MacGregor said the new arrangements would give private operators more
scope to respond to the needs of motorists without jeopardising welcome
aspects of the existing system.
'The old regime for motorway services did not always succeed in providing
drivers with the facilities they required at the right intervals,' he said.
'Although there are schemes in the pipeline, you can still drive from
Folkestone to Birmingham on the M20, M25 and M40, for example, without
meeting a single service area.'
The Council for the Protection of Rural England yesterday gave a cautious
reaction to the proposals.
'There is a real risk that developers will be looking at these new
opportunities to obtain a toehold for development in previously unavailable
countryside locations,' it said.
But they were welcomed by the Automobile Association and the Freight
Transport Association.
Editorial Comment, Page 12
</TEXT>
