<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 92 / Doubts raised on Cadbury proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SERIOUS DOUBTS over the effectiveness of the Cadbury report on corporate
governance were raised yesterday after two leading bodies representing
accountants and auditors questioned how far its code of conduct could be
enforced.
The Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales warned in a
submission to the Cadbury committee that it had 'serious misgivings' about
auditors certifying that companies had followed the code.
Separately, the Auditing Practices Board, which sets auditing standards,
dismissed as impracticable the use of auditors to check compliance with the
qualitative aspects of the code.
The concerns raise questions over the effectiveness of the Cadbury
recommendations, which have a voluntary code as their centrepiece.
The institute's financial reporting and auditing group said aspects of the
code would be impossible for auditors to verify, such as determining whether
non-executive directors were bringing independent judgment to bear on issues
of strategy and performance.
The Auditing Practices Board said auditors could only verify the objective
parts of the code. It suggested that a company's audit committee might
better certify compliance.
</TEXT>
