<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 92 / Phasing out is predicted for company car perk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BEGINNING of the end of the company car as a perk was forecast yesterday
in a report that found evidence that employers are offering cash instead.
Only a few companies have axed the company car, but many others are planning
to follow suit or offer cash instead because of diminishing tax benefits and
the recession, according to the report by Incomes Data Services.
Cash allowances instead of cars are being offered at City companies such as
Nikko Europe, Citibank, Morgan Grenfell and Merrill Lynch as well as
high-street banks such as Midland and TSB.
Companies that have stopped providing cars to staff entirely include Bankers
Trust, which made its decision because of the popularity of the allowance
alternatives and a desire to reduce costs.
Mr Ray Storry, one of the report's authors, said yesterday that employers
would continue to provide company cars when they were essential tools for
jobs, as in sales.
However, the Inland Revenue's proposals to increase tax for status cars,
generally those provided to senior managers as a perk, would lead to more
companies revising their policies.
The widespread use of company cars in the UK has always been anomalous, the
report says. UK managers traditionally earn less than their counterparts in
other countries but they are provided with better cars.
However, the climate is changing. Providing cash alternatives to cars can be
an attractive recruitment tool.
Cars Or Cash, Research File 23. IDS Top Pay Unit, Income Data Services, 193
St John St, London, EC1V 4LS.
